definition.value: Excitement that is sexual in nature.
Any sort of masturbation considered unhealthy or otherwise nonnormative.
A significant amount of masturbation considered unhealthy or otherwise nonnormative.
Normative sex play between members of different sexes and/or genders.
Nudity practiced in the home or in domestic places or situations.
Nudity of the parents in a family unit.
Any stimulus which does not involve physical contact that leads to, enhances and maintains sexual arousal, and may lead to orgasm.
Pornographic stimulus that leads to, enhances and maintains sexual arousal, and may lead to orgasm.
Nonnormative development of sexual characteristics or sex organs.
A sexual relationship which includes aspects of abuse, sexual or otherwise.
Sexual intercourse that is forced upon one, both, or more parties involved.
Any stimulus involving physical contact of the genitals with another's hand that leads to, enhances and maintains sexual arousal, and may lead to orgasm.
Manual stimulation of the clitoris primarily using a hand or hands.
Manual stimulation of the penis primarily using a hand or hands.
Any sort of clitoral erectile behavior or process considered unhealthy or otherwise nonnormative.
A condition in which clitoral erection is painful.
Any of various sexual functions which are considered nonnormative.
Any of various sexual functions which are considered normative.
Secondary sexual development induced by sex steroids from other abnormal sources (such as gonadal tumors or environmental exogenous hormones).
Masturbation performed habitually as part of a routine.
The state of overwhelming eroticism; when eroticism engulfs other qualities.
Promiscuity pursued habitually.
Promiscuity considered pathological in nature.
Dreams involving sexual components, especially those involving sexual intercourse.
An involuntary ejaculation accompanying an erotic dream.

The second stage of psychosexual development is the anal stage, spanning from the age of eighteen months to three years, wherein the infant's erogenous zone changes from the mouth (the upper digestive tract) to the anus (the lower digestive tract), while the ego formation continues.

The fifth stage of psychosexual development is the genital stage that spans puberty through adult life, and thus represents most of a person's life; its purpose is the psychological detachment and independence from the parents. The genital stage affords the person the ability to confront and resolve his or her remaining psychosexual childhood conflicts.

The fourth stage of psychosexual development is the latency stage that spans from the age of six years until puberty, wherein the child consolidates the character habits they developed in the three, earlier stages of psychologic and sexual development.

The first stage of psychosexual development is the oral stage, spanning from birth until the age of one year, wherein the infant's mouth is the focus of libidinal gratification derived from the pleasure of feeding at the mother's breast, and from the oral exploration of his or her environment, i.e. the tendency to place objects in the mouth.

The third stage of psychosexual development is the phallic stage, spanning the ages of three to six years, wherein the child's genitalia are his or her primary erogenous zone. It is in this third infantile development stage that children become aware of their bodies, the bodies of other children, and the bodies of their parents; they gratify physical curiosity by undressing and exploring each other and their genitals, and so learn the physical (sexual) differences between "male" and "female" and the gender differences between "boy" and "girl".
Nonnormative development of one's sexuality.
Normative development of one's sexuality.
Lack of development of sexual characteristics or sex organs.
Exploration of different aspects of sex and sexuality including behaviors and relationships.
Exploration of different aspects of one's own genitalia, especially in reference to sexual function.
Sexual partners in which sexual activities take place outside of the confines of romantically/sexually committed relationships.
Sexual partners who fall within the same age bracket, colloquially known as a generation.
Sexual partners who fall in different age brackets, colloquially known as a generations.
The state or quality of eroticism related to attraction to other persons, rather than to one's self (autoeroticism).
Any sort of sexual interest or process change considered unhealthy or otherwise nonnormative.
A increased interest in sexual activity or behavior or a particular kind of sexual activity or behavior.
A lowered interest in sexual activity or behavior or a particular kind of sexual activity or behavior.
An unwelcome and persistent idea, image or thought that is upsetting to an individual.
Thoughts of a sexual nature.
Thoughts of a harmful nature to oneself or others.
Thoughts of harming oneself.
Thoughts of suicide or involving suicide.
A syndrome, sometimes referred as erotomania, in which a person delusionally believes a person of higher social status (such as a celebrity) to be in love with them.
The syndrome often occurs concurrently with delusions of persecution, grandiosity, or jealousy.
Thoughts of a sexually obscene nature.
Thoughts involving sexual violence.
